These are the, and it's, it's sort of burnishing your brand. I think that's the lesson from my perspective. But as the person putting this stuff out and you go to any mall and you see like 15 different copies of it at every price point, how have you sort of managed that mentally and also within the business? Well, in terms of managing it mentally, I love the dupes. I think the dupes, first of all, the dupes make me laugh. So every time I see a fresh dup, I get a kick out of it. I think you're right. You know, I really think for the most part, the dupes are talking to another customer. And if somebody is tempted to try a dupe, as you said, they'll quickly discover that it's not, in fact, a dupe at all. It's extremely difficult to replicate what we've created with HighSport. But I think they drive the conversation. And, you know, I hope every time you see a HighSport dupe, you think of HighSport. And, and they do us a service in that way. But also, you know, you know, more than that, I think the dupes reflect the success of the idea, which is this, this, you know, in this case, a sporty and versatile silhouette that women want to wear. I think, you know, women have been attracted to the color that we've offered them. And so I know that some of these brands are trying to duplicate that and some of the colors specifically. But to me, it is, it's flattering and it's a reflection of the idea, you know, the success of the idea that we've created. You can build a business off of one product. They love to call it the hero product. But you don't seem to want to, you want to do more and you have done more. I mean, the collection is a complete collection with tops, bottoms, dresses. I went and did a personal order last season with a couple of our friends and I got a dress for the first time, which was very exciting. But what, what has the product mix right now versus when you started, whereas, where I'm sure the pants were like really driving all of it, how has the, the demand changed over the last couple of years that you've been doing this? How do you want the assortment to look? I'm incredibly grateful for the, for the attention that the pants have gotten. And I did not anticipate that they would be a hero product or the hero product. You know, that is what sort of resonated with the consumer right out of the gate. And I think that that's because the pants are emblematic of the greater concept. And the greater concept is these easy to wear, easy to style items that, you know, are super wearable, super functional, elegant and elevated and all the things that I've mentioned. And I think the pants are really emblematic of that. And, you know, that's why they've been successful or maybe stood out. But, you know, as you said, we've developed a wardrobe around the pants. And we find that a lot of women want to buy into a full look. We hear this from our stores and we see this in, you know, a lot of the selling that we, that we are able to review. I think, you know, women want a full look because they don't want to style themselves because it's, it's easier for them. And, you know, we're all looking for sort of hacks. And I think these pants are meant to make women's lives easier. And so we've offered sweaters and tops, you know, and other things that work back well to the pants. And we continue to design into this wardrobe, you know, this modular wardrobe concept. So, you know, one, we are continuing to build out the war world of the pants. So we have, of course, our classic crop pants, but we also offer a straight leg pan and a tapered pan and a longer pan and soon a shorter pan. And so, you know, we're able to serve a lot of women that way. And then we offer things that are in service to the pants like cotton the sweaters, which have been hugely popular for us and various top styles. We have a jacket that the women have really responded to and loved. And so, you know, we are continuing to, like I said, not only build out the world of the pants, but the items around it that that she can wear back to them. And the pants have afforded us the opportunity to do that in a way by having this hero product and really driving the business with the pants, we're able to continue to experiment and innovate and explore new styles and new categories and, you know, figure out really follow the customer, figure out what's resonating with her and what she likes and then follow her lead. What do you want to do with the business? Are you going to, one minor question is, well, not minor, but one thing that I'm always curious about is are you going to ever launch woven, which for the uninitiated, that just means like a shirt made of cotton that's not a stretch, that's not a knit. Like, do you have ambition to get into woven's or do you think you're going to stick with knits and then more broadly, like what is your plan in terms of scale? Do you want to be big? Do you want to ramp it up? Are you going to do DTC? That's 50 questions in one. But basically, I want to know your entire life plan from now to for the next 10 years. I don't have any, we don't have any intention to go to woven's. And that's because we want to be an expert in what we're doing. So what we are making, we want to be the go-to resource for, you know, women's knitwear, you know, and I think in this case, stretch with knitwear, so much of not everything that we make is stretch, but so much of what we make is stretch and that's what gives it its function for the most part. I think, you know, we want to be known as the resource for knitwear. And so that's where all of our focus is. And I think, first of all, there's so many people doing woven's and doing woven's really well. And I shop those brands and wear them. And, you know, I think that we're better off being experts. I also think there's a little bit of an growing inclination to shop a little bit more niche for the customer. And so by focusing what we're doing, I think that's going to give us the best ability to become experts, to serve our customer. Alyssa, you did a great job. Thank you for being here.
